William Savery ( cabinetmaker ) ( 1721 or 1722 - 1787 , Philadelphia , Pennsylvania ) was an 18th - century American cabinetmaker noted for his furniture in the Queen Anne and Philadelphia Chippendale styles .
Maria of Loon - Heinsberg ( 1426 -- 20 April 1502 ) was the daughter of John I , Count Loon - Heinsberg .
Edward Elmhirst ( 26 November 1811 -- 12 November 1893 ) was an English cricketer who played in 15 matches between 1834 and 1853 that are considered to have been first - class .
Pierre - Aimé Millet de la Turtaudière ( 1783 in Angers -- 1873 ) was a French naturalist .
Alfred Douglas Hardy ( 1870 - -1958 ) was an Australian amateur collector of freshwater algae specimens .
Julije Makanec ( 19 September 1904 , Sarajevo -- 7 June 1945 , Zagreb ) was an ethnic Croatian politician , philosopher and writer .
Isaiah Sellers ( ca . 1802 - -1864 ) was the riverboat captain from whom Samuel L. Clemens claimed to have appropriated the pen - name Mark Twain .
Gentile de ' Becchi ( 1420/1430 -- 1497 ) was an Italian bishop , diplomat , orator and writer .
George J. F. Clarke ( October 12 , 1774 -- 1836 ) was one of the most prominent and active men of East Florida in the Second Spanish Period .
José Neglia ( April 2 , 1929 -- October 10 , 1971 ) was a notable Argentine ballerino , who perhaps more than any other figure , helped popularize the classical ballet in his country .
Willard Earl Givens ( 1886 - -1971 ) was an American educator , notable as the executive secretary of the National Education Association from 1935 to 1952 .
Sir Nilratan Sircar ( 1 October 1861 -- 18 May 1943 ) was an eminent Indian doctor , educationist , philanthropist and swadeshi entrepreneur .
Thomas Watson - Wentworth , 1st Marquess of Rockingham , KB , PC ( I ) ( 13 November 1693 -- 14 December 1750 ) was a British peer and Whig politician .
Nurkhon was murdered by her own brother in 1929 for allegedly having dishonored her family by dancing in front of the public .
Murray Fife Buell ( October 5 , 1905 -- July 3 , 1975 ) was an American ecologist and palynologist .
Pepsi Tate ( 10 March 1965 -- 18 September 2007 ) was the bass guitarist of Welsh glam metal band Tigertailz , who made the Top 40 in the UK Albums Chart in the early 1990s .
Gordon Nutt ( 8 November 1932 -- 25 February 2014 ) was an English professional footballer who was a winger .
Major - General , The Reverend Denis Price CB , CBE ( 28 October 1908 -- 19 March 1966 ) was Chief of Staff , British Defence Staff in Washington from 1959 to 1962 and was later ordained into the Presbyterian Church in the USA .
Henry Pitts Forster ( 1766?--1815 ) was an orientalist .
Little Shield ( Cheyenne language : A - che - kan - koo - eni ) was a chieftain of the Northern Cheyenne from 1865 - 1879 .
Ralph Inman ( 1713 - -1788 ) was a merchant in 18th - century Boston , Massachusetts , with a residence in Cambridge .
Nicholas Clagett ( born 1685/6 , died 1746 ) was an English bishop .
Prabodh Chandra Goswami ( 1911 - -1984 ) was an Indian school teacher who worked in Jenkins School , Cooch Behar from 1951 to 1971 .
Mary , Countess of Blois , also known as Marie of Avesnes , ( 1200 - -1241 ) was countess of Blois from 1230 to 1241 .
Eric Burgin ( 4 January 1924 -- 16 November 2012 ) was an English first - class cricketer and a professional footballer .
Kaiser Kalambo ( 6 July 1953 -- 18 March 2014 ) was a Zambian coach and former footballer .
Hamlet Puleston or Puliston ( 1632 - -1662 ) was an English academic , known as a political writer .
Bruno Lohse ( 17 September 1911 -- 19 March 2007 ) was a German art dealer and SS - Hauptsturmführer who , during World War II , became the chief art looter in Paris for Hermann Göring , helping the Nazi leader amass a vast collection of plundered artworks .
General José María Flores ( 1818 , New Spain -- 1866 ) was an officer in the Mexican Army and was a member of la otra banda .
Clarrie Horder died on 6 June 1960 at St. George Hospital , aged 69 .
John Dennant ( 1839 -- 12 June 1907 ) was an English - born educational administrator and geologist , president of the Royal Society of Victoria in 1903 .
José María Ruda ( Buenos Aires , 1924 -- Spain , 7 July 1994 ) was an Argentine jurist .
Katharine Mary Briggs ( 8 November 1898 -- 15 October 1980 ) was a British folklorist and writer , who wrote The Anatomy of Puck , the four - volume A Dictionary of British Folk - Tales in the English Language , and various other books on fairies and folklore .
Richard Clipston Sturgis Jr. ( 1880 - -1910 ) was born in Brookline , Massachusetts , the son of noted architect R. Clipston Sturgis .
Attakullakulla ( Cherokee , Ata - gul ' kalu ; often called Little Carpenter by the English ) ( c. 1708 - -1778 ) was an influential Cherokee leader and the tribe 's First Beloved Man , serving from 1761 to around 1775 .
Sir Neil Loring ( `` Loryng '' , `` Loringe '' etc . , Neel alias Nigel , Latin : Nigellus ) ( c. 1320 -- 18 March 1386 ) , KG , was a medieval English soldier and diplomat and a founding member of the Order of the Garter , established by King Edward III in 1348 .
Georg Ritschel ( 1616 - -1683 ) was a Bohemian Protestant minister and educator .
William Henry Schofield ( 1870 - 1920 ) was an American academic , founder of the Harvard Studies in Comparative Literature .
James Ogilvy , 1st Earl of Airlie ( c. 1593 -- 1666 ) was a Scottish royalist of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms .
The Honourable William George Boyle ( 12 August 1830 -- 24 March 1908 ) was a British soldier and Liberal Party politician .
Henning Larsen , Hon . FAIA ( 20 August 1925 -- 22 June 2013 ) was a Danish architect .
Sergio Campanato ( 17 February 1930 -- 1 March 2005 ) was an Italian mathematician who studied the theory of regularity for elliptic and parabolic partial differential equations .
Iago ab Idwal ap Meurig ( died 1039 ) was a Prince of Gwynedd .
Erminio Macario ( 27 May 1902 -- 25 March 1980 ) , best known as Macario , was an Italian film actor and comedian .
Charles Anthony Goessmann ( 13 June 1827 Naumburg - 1 September 1910 Amherst , Massachusetts ) , known in his native German as Karl Anton Goessmann , was a Massachusetts agricultural and food chemist .
Walter K. Link ( 1902 - 1982 ) was an American oil geologist .
Aleksandar Tomašević ( Serbian Cyrillic : Александар Томашевић ; 19 November 1908 -- 21 February 1988 ) was a Serbian football player and manager .
King Hagler or Nopkehee ( ca . 1700 - -1763 ) was a chief or King of the Catawba Native American tribe from 1754 to 1763 .
Jacques Fabien Gautier d'Agoty ( 1716 - -1785 ) was a French anatomist , painter and printmaker .
Norman Sheffield ( 25 September 1939 - 20 June 2014 ) was a music and advertising industry figure , most noted for his music industry recording and management roles , ownership of the former Trident Studios , and being the first manager of the rock band Queen .
William Imbrie ( 1 January 1845 - 4 August 1928 ) was an American missionary to Japan .
Elias Degiannis ( Greek : Ηλίας Ντεγιάννης ) ( 22 December 1912 -- 18 June 1943 ) was a Greek navy officer and second in command of the resistance group PROMETHEUS .
Philip Guedalla ( 12 March 1889 -- 16 December 1944 ) was a British barrister , and a popular historical and travel writer and biographer .
Lieutenant Colonel Sir Frederick Harrison ( 1844 - 31 December 1914 ) was a British army officer , and railway manager .
Guan Liang ( Chinese : 关良 ; 1900 - -1986 ) , courtesy name Lianggong ( 良公 ) , was a Chinese painter .
Francesco Canova da Milano ( Francesco da Milano , also known as Il divino , Francesco da Parigi , etc . ) ( 18 August 1497 -- 2 January 1543 ) was an Italian lutenist and composer .
Tom Pook ( 1869 -- 21 February 1948 ) was an English - born Wales international rugby forward who played rugby union for Newport and rugby league with Holbeck .
Joyce Windsor ( 21 January 1932 - 15 October 2008 ) was an English - born actress perhaps best remembered for her portrayal of the cleaner Ruby in the BBC1 Comedy Butterflies by Carla Lane .
Charles Maurin ( 1 April 1856 -- 22 July 1914 ) was a French painter , engraver , and an anarchist who practiced a variety of styles .
Henry Lowther Clarke ( 23 November 1850 -- 23 June 1926 ) was the fourth Anglican bishop and first archbishop of Melbourne , Australia .
Gino Cantarelli ( 1899 -- 1950 ) was an Italian Dadaist poet and painter of the early 20th century .
Pál Beőthy de Bessenyő et Örvend ( Beöthy ; 20 June 1866 -- 15 September 1921 ) was a Hungarian jurist , soldier and politician , who served as Speaker of the House of Representatives between 1913 and 1917 .
Pieter Godfried Bertichen ( 5 February 1796 -- 1856 ) was a Dutch painter and lithographer who also lived and worked in Brazil .
Sidney Sinclair ( 1915 - -1999 ) was an English born , Australian businessman , philanthropist , trade advisor to the Federal Government and prominent member of the Australian Jewish community .
Helen Schnabel , née Fogel , ( 22 July 1911 -- 29 September 1974 ) was an American pianist .
Arthur Annesley , 5th Earl of Anglesey PC , PC ( Ire ) ( c. 1678 -- 31 March 1737 ) was an Anglo - Irish politician .
Jimmy Mitchell ( born 22 October 1924 ; died 2004 ) was a Scottish footballer , who played for Queen 's Park , Morton , Aberdeen and was player / manager of Cowdenbeath .
Walter Geikie ( 10 November 1795 -- 1 August 1837 ) , was a short - lived Scottish painter , operational in the early 19th century .
Mao Mengsuo ( simplified Chinese : 毛梦索 ; traditional Chinese : 毛夢索 ; pinyin : Máo Mèngsuǒ , 15 June 1989 -- 12 June 2010 ) was a Chinese footballer , previously played in NT Realty Wofoo Tai Po .
Robert Waring Stoddard ( 1906 - -1984 ) was President of Wyman - Gordon , a major industrial enterprise , and one of the founders of the anticommunist John Birch Society .
Lionel Bailey Budden FRIBA ( 1877 -- 21 July 1956 ) , a British architect , was the son of William Budden and Elizabeth Adams .
William Dawson Lawrence ( 16 July 1817 -- 8 December 1886 ) was a successful shipbuilder , businessman and politician .
F. M. Khan ( 1930 - -2002 ) was born in Bargu , a village in the district Ghizer , in the Gilgit - Baltistan region of Pakistan .
Milan Babić ( Serbian Cyrillic : Милан Бабић ; 26 February 1956 -- 5 March 2006 ) was from 1991 to 1992 the first President of the Republic of Serbian Krajina , a self - proclaimed state largely populated by Serbs of Croatia that wished to break away from Croatia .
William Harry ( 30 November 1878 -- 21 February 1943 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played for Carlton in one game in 1906 .
Maurice Persat ( Puy - de - Dôme , Ennezat April 30 , 1788 - 1858 ) , a French officer and writer , participant of the Napoleonic wars and revolutionary wars in Latin America , Greece and Spain .
Nicholas Caldecote ( died 1443 ) , of Meldreth , Cambridgeshire , was an English politician .
Matthew Gibney ( 1 November 1835 in Killeshandra , Cavan , Ireland -- 22 June 1925 in Perth , Western Australia ) , an Australian metropolitan bishop , was the third Roman Catholic Bishop of Perth , serving from 1886 until 1910 .
Santo Rinaldi ( 1620 - -1676 ) was an Italian painter of the Baroque period .
Sir William Fenwick , 2nd Baronet ( c. 1617 - 9 July 1676 ) , was an English landowner and politician who sat in the House of Commons at various times between 1645 and 1676 .
Frieda Lauth ( 1879 London - 4 May 1949 Durban ) was a South African botanical artist who emigrated to Natal with her parents in 1882 .
Grey Beard ( b : ? , d. 1875 ) was a Southern Cheyenne medicine man and chief .
Carl Adolph Grevesmühl ( 1744 - -1827 ) was a Swedish businessman from Stockholm .
General Maha Bandula ( Burmese : မဟာဗန္ဓုလ ( məhà bàɴdṵla̰ ) ; 6 November 1782 -- 1 April 1825 ) was commander - in - chief of the Royal Burmese Armed Forces from 1821 until his death in 1825 in the First Anglo - Burmese War .
Sir Richard Kaye , 6th Baronet , FRS ( 1736 - -25 December 1809 ) was an English churchman and scientist .
Pierre Guffroy ( 22 April 1926 -- 27 September 2010 ) was a French production designer and art director .
Sai Jinhua ( traditional Chinese : 賽金花 ; simplified Chinese : 赛金花 ; pinyin : Sài Jīnhuā ; Wade -- Giles : Sai Chin - hua ; `` Prettier Than Golden Flower '' ; circa 1872 - 1936 ) was a Chinese courtesan who became the acquaintance of Alfred von Waldersee .
Clemente Biondetti ( 18 August 1898 -- 24 February 1955 ) was an Italian auto racing driver .
Richard C. Snyder ( 21 August 1916 -- 9 December 1997 ) was an American political scientist who specialized in foreign policy .
Scott Sherrin ( London , 31 May 1972 - March 1996 ) was a multi - talented child star .
Monsignor John Joseph Egan ( 9 October 1916 -- 19 May 2001 ) was an American Roman Catholic priest and social activist .
Benedict of Poland ( Latin : Benedictus Polonus , Polish Benedykt Polak ) ( ca . 1200 -- ca . 1280 ) was a Polish Franciscan friar , traveler , explorer , and interpreter .
F. D. Benteen ( died 1864 ) was an American sheet music publisher and composer during the 19th century , based out of Baltimore , Maryland .
Lord Pretender ( 8 September 1917 -- 22 January 2002 ) was the stage name of Aldric Farrell , M.O.M. , H.B.M. a calypsonian vocalist born on the island of Tobago widely acknowledged to be a `` master '' of extempo , a lyrically improvised form of calypso music considered a forerunner of rap .
Connie Ediss ( 11 August 1871 -- 18 April 1934 ) was an English actress best known as a buxom , good - humoured comedienne in many of the popular Edwardian musical comedies around the turn of the 20th century .
George van Parris ( died 1551 ) was a Dutch Arian , who was burnt at the stake in London by his fellow Protestants .
Annie Shepley Omori ( 1856 -- 1943 ) was an American artist , activist , and translator .
Dame Anne Mills McEwen DBE ( 1900 -- 10 February 1967 ) , known as Annie McEwen , was an Australian social activist , and the wife of John McEwen ( who after her death became Prime Minister of Australia ) .
Edgar Krahn ( 1 October ( O.S. 19 September ) 1894 in Laiuse Parish -- 6 March 1961 ) was an Estonian mathematician .
Augustus Henry Fox ( c. 1822 - -1895 ) was a painter who exhibited three works at the Royal Academy .
Hua Tuo ( c. 140 - -208 ) , courtesy name Yuanhua , was an ancient Chinese physician who lived in the late Eastern Han Dynasty .
George Hewitt Cushman ( June 5 , 1814 in Windham , Connecticut -- August 3 , 1876 in Jersey City Heights , New Jersey ) was a top American engraver and painter of miniature paintings and portraits of his time ( second only to Edward Greene Malbone ) .
Frank Sturdy Sinnatt FRS ( 4 May 1880 - 27 January 1943 ) was a British fuel engineer .
Annie French ( 1873 - -1965 ) was a Scottish painter , engraver , illustrator , and designer associated with the Glasgow School .
Sharad Vaidya ( 7 March 1936 - 19 October 2000 ) was an Indian surgeon who specialized in cancer surgery .
Patrick Oliver Walsh ( 13 July 1937 -- 9 March 1996 ) , better known as Ollie Walsh , was an Irish sportsperson .
Wally Powell ( 31 March 1878 -- 7 July 1945 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Carlton in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Margaret R. Manning ( died 1984 ) was an American journalist and book reviewer .
Fanchea died c. 585 of natural causes and is buried at Killane , Ireland .
Sayyid Muhammad ibn Ali as - Senussi ( 1787 - -1859 ) was the founder of the Senussi order .
Ivo Krbek ( 23 August 1890 -- 17 January 1966 ) was a Croatian politician , lawyer , lecturer , and academic in the Kingdom of Yugoslavia , the Independent State of Croatia , and the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia .
George Henry Bolsover CBE OBE ( 18 November 1910 -- 15 April 1990 ) was the director of the School of Slavonic and East European Studies at the University of London from 1947 - -76 .
Guy XIII de Laval , born Jean de Montfort , ( 1385- 14 August 1414 , Rhodes ) was seigneur of Laval and of Kergorlay .
Edward Atkyns Bray ( 1778 - -1857 ) was a British poet , vicar , and miscellaneous writer .
John Skehan ( 1922 -- 18 November 1992 ) was a prolific broadcaster on RTÉ , radio and television , for four decades .
Carlos Olivier ( Carlos Raúl Fernández Olivier ) ( 26 January 1952 -- 22 January 2007 ) , was a Venezuelan actor , famous for his roles in telenovelas , including Leonela , El País de las Mujeres , Viva la Pepa , Las González , Engañada , and Los Querendones .
Lê Quý Đôn ( 黎貴惇 , 1726 - -1784 ) was an 18th - century Vietnamese philosopher , poet , encyclopedist , and government official .
Johann Flierl ( 16 April 1858 -- 30 September 1947 ) , was a pioneer Lutheran missionary in New Guinea .
Elise Otté ( 30 September 1818 -- 20 December 1903 ) was an Anglo - Danish linguist , scholar and historian .
John Buzzell ( 1766 - 1863 ) was an early proponent of the Free Will Baptist Church , a Christian author , and a preacher .
Caleb Evans ( 25 July 1831 -- 16 September 1886 ) , was an English geologist .
Sam You d ( 16 April 1922 -- 3 February 2012 ) , known professionally as Christopher Samuel You d , was a British writer , best known for science fiction under the pseudonym John Christopher , including the novels The Death of Grass , The Possessors , and the young - adult novel series The Tripods .
Wondosson Kassa , also known as Wond Wossen Kassa , ( 1903 -- 19 December 1936 ) was a member of the royalty of the Ethiopian Empire , an army commander , and a patriot .
John Hollings or Hollins , M.D. ( 1683?--1739 ) was an English physician .
Benjamin C. Marsh ( 1878 - 1952 ) was a social worker , journalist , and Georgist activist who helped pioneer the city planning movement in the United States .
Dame Marjorie Parker , DBE ( 1900 -- 18 February 1991 ) , known as Margot Parker , was an Australian civic and political activist who was created a Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire in 1977 .
Joseph Kleitsch ( 1882 - -1931 ) was a Hungarian - American portrait and plein air painter who holds a high place in the early California School of Impressionism .
Joseph P. Guth ( 1860-April 1928 ) was a popular civil engineer , architect and builder in Omaha , Nebraska starting in the 1880s .
Emmanuele Vitale ( 30 April 1758 -- 8 October 1802 ) was a Maltese notary , commander and statesman .
Harold Barnwell died on 25 August 1917 while test flying the prototype Vickers Vampire night fighter at Joyce Green , Kent .
William Dorrinton ( 29 April 1809 -- 8 November 1848 ) was an English cricketer for Kent , Hampshire , Suffolk and the Marylebone Cricket Club in a 94 - -match first -- class career which began in 1836 and lasted until 1847 , a year before his death .
Sir Henry Vere Huntley ( 1795 -- 7 May 1864 ) was an English naval officer and colonial administrator .
Yitzchok Yaakov Weiss ( 1902 - -1989 ) , also known as the Minchas Yitzchak , was a prominent Dayan , Halachic authority and Talmudic scholar .
Edwin Brockholst Livingston ( 1852 - 1929 ) was an amateur historian .
Amalie Mathilde Bauerle ( 12 November 1873 -- 4 March 1916 ) , known as Amelia Bauerle , was a British painter , illustrator and etcher .
Samuel Parsons Scott ( 8 July 1846 -- 30 May 1929 ) , known as S.P. Scott , was an American attorney , banker , and scholar .
William Neil Tompkins ( 15 January 1927 -- 20 February 1991 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Geelong in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Florence Esté ( 1860 - -1926 ) was an American painter in oils , watercolors and pastels and an etcher and engraver , born in Cincinnati , Ohio .
Bert Carey ( 30 May 1905 -- 10 July 1994 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Fitzroy and Hawthorn in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Beulah Elfreth Kennard ( August 3 , 1869 -- after 1944 ) was the educational director of the Association of Department Store Workers , president of the Pennsylvania Association of Women Workers , and president of the Pittsburgh Playground Association from 1900 to 1918 .
Erica Reiner ( 4 August 1924 -- 31 December 2005 ) was an American Assyriologist and author .
Bin Bucheng ( simplified Chinese : 宾步程 ; traditional Chinese : 賓步程 ; pinyin : Bīn Bùchéng ; 12 January 1880- 27 December 1943 ) was a Chinese politician and educator .

Elijah Masinde ( also spelt Elija Masinde ) ( 1910 - -12 ( ? ) --1987 ) was a Bukusu freedom - fighter .
Arthur René Jean Baptiste Bavay ( 29 April 1840 , Lamballe -- 1923 ) was a French pharmacist , herpetologist and malacologist .
Bobby Haarms ( 8 March 1934 -- 6 June 2009 ) was a Dutch professional football player and coach .
Helen Margaret Gilkey ( 1886 - -1972 ) was a pioneering mycologist and botanist .
Sir William Leighton ( /ˈleɪtən/ ; c. 1565 - -1622 ) was an Elizabethan composer and editor who published The Teares and Lamentatacions of a Sorrowfull Soule ( 1614 ) which comprised 55 pieces by 21 composers ( among them John Bull , William Byrd , John Dowland and Martin Peerson ) , including eight by himself .
Hartley Howard ( 1908 - -1979 ) was a pen name of Leopold Horace Ognall , a British crime novelist .
Henry George Keith ( 1899 - 1982 ) , known as Harry Keith , was a British forester and plant collector .
Edmond André Coralie Schietekat ( 17 December 1933 -- 19 October 1981 ) pseudonym Paul Snoek , was a Belgian poet .
Marek Weber ( 24 October 1888 - 9 February 1964 ) was a German violinist and bandleader .
Robert Furber ( 1674 - -1756 ) was a British horticulturist and author , best known for writing the first seed catalogue produced in England .
John Mahony ( 1863 - -1943 ) was a famous Irish sportsperson .
Wilhelm Zander ( 22 April 1911 -- 27 September 1974 ) was an adjutant to Martin Bormann during World War II . He survived the war and died in Munich in 1974 .
Ralph Keene ( 1902 - -1963 ) was an Indian - born British screenwriter , producer and film director .
George William Card , F.G.S. , A.R.S.M. ( ? -- 2 June 1943 ) was an Australian petrographer .
Peter Furneaux ( 12 October 1935 -- 2 December 2014 ) was an English football club chairman and investor .
Viv Thicknesse ( 1910 - -1986 ) was an Australian dual - code rugby half - back , a state representative in both rugby league and rugby union .
Farnobius ( died AD 377 ) was a Gothic chief who was killed in a battle with the Roman army of Frigeridus while trying to cross the mountains from Thrace into Illyricum .
Thomas Worsnop ( 2 February 1821 -- 24 January 1898 ) was an Australian colonial militia , historian , local government official and town clerk .
Olive Riley ( 20 October 1899 -- 12 July 2008 ) was an Australian centenarian woman , born in Broken Hill , New South Wales , believed for a time to have been the world 's oldest online personal blogger .
Kei Suma ( Japanese : すまけい ; 4 September 1935 -- 7 December 2013 ) was a Japanese film and television actor , whose career spanned 25 years .
George Enoch Grayson ( 1833 ( or 1834 ) -- 7 November 1912 ) , usually known as G. E. Grayson , was an English architect who practised in Liverpool .
Philip Hutchins Rogers ( 1794 - -1853 ) was an English marine and landscape painter .
Abu Abdallah Mohammed ibn Qasim ibn Zakur ( died 1708 ) was a Moroccan poet , historian and travel writer from Fes .
Gao Jian ( 576 -- February 14 , 647 ) , courtesy name Shilian , better known as Gao Shilian , formally Duke Wenxian of Shen ( 申文獻公 ) , was a chancellor of the Tang dynasty .
André Gagnaux ( died February 1996 ) , who was a Swiss , was the first President of the World Confederation of Billiard Sports ( WCBS ) and the former President of the Union Mondiale de Billard ( UMB ) .
Jabez Carter Hornblower ( 21 May 1744 -- 14 July 1814 ) was an English pioneer of steam power , and the son of Jonathan Hornblower .
Marie - Denise Villers ( née Lemoine ; 1774 -- 19 August 1821 ) was a French painter who specialized in portraits .
Joseph Dickson ( April 1745 -- April 1825 ) was an American politician and soldier who represented North Carolina 's 1st district in the United States House of Representatives from 1799 1801 , and would later serve in the Tennessee House of Representatives .
Giovanni Battista Pagliari ( 1741- January 8 , 1816 ) was an Italian painter and art restorer .
Sir William Moleyns ( 1378 - -1425 ) , from Stoke Poges , Buckinghamshire , was an English politician .
Juan Lovera ( 11 July 1776 , Caracas - 29 January 1841 , Caracas ) was a Venezuelan painter , best known for his portraits and historical scenes relating to his country 's independence movement .
Sir James Stonhouse , 11th Baronet ( 1716 - -1795 ) was an English physician and cleric , known as a hospital founder and religious writer .
Hildegarde of Burgundy ( c. 1056 - -1104 ) was a French noblewoman .
Vincent Contenson ( born at Altivillare ( Gers ) , Diocese of Condon , 1641 ; died Creil - sur - Oise , 26 December 1674 ) was a French Dominican theologian and preacher .
Elizabeth Lowell Putnam ( 2 February 1862 - 1935 ) was born ( as Bessie Lowell ) in Boston , Massachusetts , the daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Augustus Lowell of Boston .
Kebek Sultan Oghlan ( died c. 1472 ) was Khan of eastern Moghulistan ( Uyghurstan ) from 1468 or 1469 until his death .
Fred C. Blanck ( October 14 , 1881 -- 1965 ) was an American food scientist who was involved in the founding of the Institute of Food Technologists ( IFT ) which was involved in the publishing of food and nutrition articles and books .
Bade Ghulam Ali Khan ( Devanagari:बड़े ग़ुलाम अली ख़ान , Shahmukhi / Urdu : بڑے غلام علی خان ) ( c. 2 April 1902 -- 23 April 1968 ) was a Hindustani classical vocalist , from the Kasur Patiala Gharana .
William Field Porter ( 1784 - -1869 ) was a ship owner from Liverpool , who migrated to South Australia in 1839 .
Thistle Yolette Harris ( born 29 July 1902 and died 5 July 1990 ) , also known as Thistle Stead , was an Australian botanist , educator , author and conservationist .
Arturo Vergara Medina ( 1928 - 1986 ) , better known by his stage name Bentot or Ben Cosca , was a Filipino comedian and vaudevillian who spent most of his career under LVN Pictures .
Jean Joseph Guieu , also Jean Guyeux , ( 30 September 1758 - 5 October 1817 ) joined the French royal army and quickly rose in rank during the French Revolutionary Wars .
Dr Edith Clara Batho ( 21 September 1895 -- 21 January 1986 ) was Principal of Royal Holloway College , University of London ( RHC ) from 1945 - 1962 .
John Raymond Hobbs MRCS , FRCP , FRCPath , FRCPaed ( 17 April 1929 -- 13 July 2008 ) was a professor who was at the forefront of the techniques of clinical immunology , protein biochemistry and bone marrow transplantation , specifically in child health .
Rodrig Goliescu ( 1882 - -1942 ) was a Romanian inventor , engineer , and Lieutenant , who built the avioplan , the first airplane with a tubular fuselage . The model , with a length of 1.2 m was successfully tested in 1909 , having a take off angle of 30 degrees .
Astrid Hjertenæs Andersen ( 5 September 1915 -- 21 April 1985 ) was a Norwegian poet and travel - writer .
Henry , Duke of Parma and Piacenza ( Italian : Enrico Maria Alberto Ferdinando Carlo Pio Luigi Antonio di Borbone - Parma e Piacenza ; 13 June 1873 -- 16 November 1939 ) was the head of the House of Bourbon - Parma and the pretender to the defunct throne of Parma from 1907 to 1939 .
Mario Pirani Coen ( 3 August 1925 -- 18 April 2015 ) was an Italian journalist , economist , and writer .
George Courtney Benson ( 1886 - -1960 ) was an Australian painter , muralist and cartoonist , and an official war artist during World War I.
Santiago Martínez Delgado ( 1906 - -1954 ) was a Colombian painter , sculptor , art historian and writer .
John Farr Abbott , sometimes Abbot ( 1756 -- 22 September 1794 ) was a British barrister .
Victor - Alphonse Huard ( born Joseph - Alphonse , sometimes given as Joseph - Victor Alphonse ; 28 February 1853 - -15 October 1929 ) was a French - Canadian churchman , naturalist , writer and editor .
Arthur Staples ( 2 February 1899 -- 1965 ) was an English footballer who played in the Football League for Mansfield Town .
Caleb Gibbs ( 1748 - -1818 ) was the first commander of the Commander - in - Chief 's Guard , the unit that protected General George Washington during the American Revolutionary War .
Victor Keppler ( 1904 -- 2 December 1987 ) was an American commercial photographer and author .
Haralamb H. Georgescu ( 1908 - -1977 ) , also known as Harlan Georgesco , was a twentieth century Romanian - American modernist architect .
Peter Maag ( Ernst Peter Johannes Maag ) ( 10 May 1919 -- 16 April 2001 ) was a Swiss conductor .
John William Woolsey ( 26 July 1767 -- 9 May 1853 ) was a Canadian businessman born at Quebec .
Joe Slater ( 29 November 1888 -- 3 May 1917 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Geelong in the Victorian Football League .
Walter de Stapledon ( or Stapeldon ) ( 1 February 1261 -- 15 October 1326 ) was Bishop of Exeter 1308 - -1326 and twice Lord High Treasurer of England , in 1320 and 1322 .
Princess Patricia of Connaught ( Victoria Patricia Helena Elizabeth ; later Lady Patricia Ramsay ; 17 March 1886 -- 12 January 1974 ) was a granddaughter of Queen Victoria .
Father Nicholas Couris ( born 1896 - died 3(16 ) August 1977 ) was an officer in the Imperial Russian Army , and combat veteran of the White Army during the Russian Civil War , and , in his old age , a priest of the Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia stationed in Dublin , Ireland .
Thomas John Barnardo ( 4 July 1845 -- 19 September 1905 ) was an Irish philanthropist and founder and director of homes for poor children .

Edith Constance Holme ( 7 October 1880 -- 17 June 1955 ) , married name Punchard , was an English writer and playwright .
Stephen of Senlis ( died 6 May 1142 ) was archdeacon of Notre Dame de Paris .
Robert Boyd , 1st Lord Boyd ( died c. 1482 ) Lord Boyd , was a Scottish statesman .
Christopher ( John Williams ) Nesham ( 1771 --4 November 1853 ) , admiral , born in 1771 , was son of Christopher Nesham , a captain in the 63rd regiment , by his wife Mary Williams , sister of William Peere Williams - Freeman , admiral of the fleet .
Loyal Oakley ( 20 November 1898 -- 4 July 1990 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Richmond in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Zevulun Hammer ( Hebrew : זבולון המר‎ , 31 May 1936 -- 20 January 1998 ) was an Israeli politician , minister and Deputy Prime Minister .

Gommaert van der Gracht or Gommaer van der Gracht ( c. 1590 - 1639 ) was a Flemish painter and draughtsman mainly known for his still life and landscape paintings .
Raymond Barkway ( 1924 - -1956 ) ran the 110 M high hurdles for Great Britain in the 1948 London Olympics .
Peta Nocona 's wife and children were captured and his band scattered on December 18 , 1860 by Captain Lawrence Sullivan Ross and his Texas Rangers and Militia at the Battle of Pease River .

William George Storm ( 1826 - -1892 ) was a Canadian architect who designed a number of prominent monuments in Toronto .

Ole Edvard Borgen ( 8 November 1925 -- 24 March 2009 ) was a Norwegian theologian and Methodist bishop .
Beniamino Carelli ( 9 May 1833 -- 14 February 1921 ) was a celebrated Italian singing teacher and composer .

Margaret Maxwell Inglis ( née Murray ; 27 October 1774 -- 21 December 1843 ) was a Scottish poet commended by Robert Burns .
Terje Bergstad ( 14 October 1938 -- 7 February 2014 ) was a Norwegian painter and printmaker .

Nathaniel Colver ( born in Orwell , Vermont , 10 May 1794 ; died in Chicago , 25 December 1870 ) was a United States Baptist clergyman .
Charles Howard , 3rd Earl of Carlisle , PC ( c.1669 -- 1 May 1738 ) was a British statesman and member of the peerage of England .
Harold Koplow ( November 21 , 1940 -- November 4 , 2004 ) , an American computer scientist and one of the early developers of office automation equipment , was raised in Lynn , Massachusetts .
Sigurd Engelstad ( August 2 , 1914 - - January 16 , 2006 ) was a Norwegian genealogist and archivist .
Abraham Godijn or Abraham Godyn ( alternative spellings of family name : Goddijn and Abraham Goddyn ) ( 1655/56 -- after 1724 ) was a Flemish painter who , after a stay in Italy , worked for a time as a court painter in Prague where he produced magnificent Baroque frescos .
Georg II , Duke of Saxe - Meiningen ( Meiningen , 2 April 1826 -- Wildungen , 25 June 1914 ) , was the penultimate Duke of Saxe - Meiningen , reigning from 1866 to 1914 .
Giovanni Battista de Marinis ( died 1669 ) was the Master of the Order of Preachers from 1650 to 1669 .
Fănică Luca ( born Ştefan Luca Iordache ; 5 April 1894 -- 26 October 1968 ) was a Romani - Romanian musician and a pan pipe ( nai or musical in Romanian ) virtuoso , who was the first to make this instrument popular outside his own country .
Michalis Vardanis ( Greek : Μιχάλης Βαρδάνης , 1936 -- 14 January 2014 ) was a Greek Army officer , lawyer and a major figure in the resistance against the Regime of the Colonels .
Baba Faja Martaneshi ( 1910 - 18 March 1947 ) was an Albanian Bektashi baba ( Sufi ) and a resistance leader during the National Liberation War of the Albanian People .
Ryszard S. Michalski died on 20 September 2007 from cancer at his home in Fairfax .

William Salmon ( 1644 - -1713 ) was English empiric doctor , advertising himself as `` Professor of Physick '' , and a writer of medical texts .
Cuthbert Burby ( died 1607 ) was a London bookseller and publisher of the Elizabethan and early Jacobean eras .

Edward Wigglesworth ( c. 1693 - -1765 ) was a clergyman , teacher and theologian in Colonial America .

María Luisa Pérez - Caballero Moltó ( 1923 - -1995 ) , commonly known by her stage name Marilú Elízaga , was a Spanish actress of theatre , television , and film .
S. E. Krupa Rao ( 1939 - -1993 ) was a Pastor of the Protestant Convention of Baptist Churches of Northern Circars where he held leadership positions in the Church society whose area of operation extended from Srikakulam District in the northern circars along the Bay of Bengal right through seven districts up to Guntur District .
Kotla Vijaya Bhaskara Reddy ( 16 August 1920 -- 27 September 2001 ) was the chief minister of the Indian state of Andhra Pradesh on two occasions , in 1983 and then from 1992 to 1994 .
Jason Farradane , born Jason Lewkowitch ( 29 September 1906 -- 27 June 1989 ) was a Polish - born British librarian .
György Sándor ( Hungarian pronunciation : ( ˈɟørɟ ˈʃaːndor ) ; 21 September 1912 -- 9 December 2005 ) was a Hungarian pianist and writer .
Sir John Plowright Houfton ( 13 December 1857 -- 18 November 1929 ) was a British colliery owner and politician from Mansfield in Nottinghamshire .
Matthew Derbyshire Mann ( 1844 - -1921 ) was one of the physicians who attended President William McKinley after he had been shot by Leon Czolgosz .
Francisco de la Torre ( floruit 1483 - -1504 ) was a Spanish composer mainly active in the Kingdom of Naples .
Francis X. Murphy ( June 16 , 1914 - -2002 ) was a Redemptorist chaplain and theology professor .
John Duncan Martin Derrett ( more usually J Duncan M Derrett ) ( 30 August 1922 -- 21 October 2012 ) was Professor of Oriental Laws in the University of London , from 1965 to 1982 , and afterwards Emeritus Professor .
Jeremiah Colegrove ( 31 July 1758 -- 26 August 1836 ) was born to William Colegrove in Scituate , Rhode Island .
Dr. Orison Swett Marden ( 1848 - -1924 ) was an American inspirational author who wrote about achieving success in life and founded SUCCESS magazine in 1897 .
Sándor Nemes , also known as Alexander Neufeld ( 25 September 1899 -- 27 October 1977 ) was an Hungarian football player and menager .
Esta Henry or Esther Henry ( 1883 - -1963 ) was an antique dealer in Edinburgh , Scotland .
Qian Shizhen ( Chinese : 錢世楨 ; 1561 - -1642 ) was a Ming dynasty general who participated in the Imjin war .
Uberto Mori ( 28 January 1926 -- 6 September 1989 ) was an Italian layman who served as a lecturer in Bologna and was also an entrepreneur .
Anne of Auvergne also known as Anna d'Auvergne ( 1358 -- Moulins 22 September 1417 ) was the only child of Beraud II , Dauphin of Auvergne and his first wife Jeanne of Forez .
John Thomas Donovan ( 1878 -- 17 January 1922 ) was an Irish barrister and nationalist politician who sat in the House of Commons from 1914 to 1918 .
Edwin Henry Mason Smith died on in the Cornwell Public Hospital , Epsom , Auckland on 15 October 1971 at an age of 85 and was buried at Waikumete Cemetery on the 16th .
Ernest Phipps ( 1900 - -1963 ) was an Old Time Country musician and Southern Gospel singer best known for his recordings at the Bristol Sessions in 1928 .
Edward E. Simbalist ( 5 September 1943 -- 12 March 2005 ) was a role - playing game designer .
Tibor Perecsi ( 18 October 1941 -- 17 February 2014 ) was a Hungarian footballer , who was part of the Ferencváros team that won the 1964 - -65 Inter - Cities Fairs Cup .
Yang Zaisi ( 楊再思 ) ( died 709 ) , formally Duke Gong of Zheng ( 鄭恭公 ) , was an official of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty and Wu Zetian 's Zhou Dynasty , serving several times as chancellor during the reigns of Wu Zetian and her son Emperor Zhongzong .
Heinrich Neal ( September 11 , 1870 -- 1940 ) was a German Capellmeister at Heidelberg , born to the artist David Dalhoff Neal and Marie Ainmiller , and brother to dramatist Maximilian Dalhoff Neal .
Per Ulven ( 31 October 1925 -- 15 December 2009 ) is a Norwegian harness racer .
John Fulford ( died 12 June 1518 ) was an English archdeacon .
Serafino Tramezzini or Tramazzini ( Ascoli Piceno , January 21 , 1859 - 1893 ) was an Italian sculptor .
Nicholas Skerrett ( died 1583 ) was a Roman Catholic clergyman who was Archbishop of Tuam in Ireland from 1580 to 1583 .
Salauddin Mumtaz ( Bengali : সালাহউদ্দিন মমতাজ ; 1945 -- 31 July 1971 ) was a military officer who fought for the separatist side in the 1971 Bangladeshi War of Independence .
Henry Robert Morland ( 1716/1719 -- 30 November 1797 ) was an English portrait painter , best remembered for a portrait of King George III , and for being the father of the animal painter George Morland .
Magdalena Stenbock ( 14 September 1649 -- 24 January 1727 ) , was a politically active Swedish countess and salon holder .
Sverre Brodahl ( 26 January 1909 -- 2 November 1998 ) was a Norwegian Nordic skier who competed in the 1930s .
Monte Montague ( 23 April 1891 -- 6 April 1959 ) was the stage name for Walter H. Montague , an American film actor .
John Sotheby ( 1740 - -1807 ) was an English auctioneer , who is the eponym of the famous auction house Sotheby 's .
Lillian Exum Clement ( 1894 - -1925 ) , also known as Lillian Stafford after marrying , was the first woman elected to the North Carolina General Assembly and the first woman to serve in any state legislature in the Southern United States .
Chaudhry Fateh Muhammad Sial ( 1887 - -1960 ) was a companion of Mirza Ghulam Ahmad and the first Ahmadi Muslim missionary sent from India , under the leadership of Hakeem Noor - ud - Din , the first Khalifa of the Ahmadiyya movement .
Al Fagaly ( 5 January 1909 - 23 April 1963 ) was a U.S. cartoonist and creator of the Super Duck and There Oughta Be a Law ! comic strips .
Zena Dare ( 4 February 1887 -- 11 March 1975 ) was an English singer and actress who was famous for her performances in Edwardian musical comedy and other musical theatre and comedic plays in the first half of the 20th century .
Walter de Saleron ( aka Walter of London ) , sixth Archbishop of Tuam , 1257 - 1258 .
Alexander W. Brewster ( 5 June 1796 - 6 May 1851 ) was a prominent merchant and manufacturer , as well as a politician and educator in Erie , Pennsylvania .
Wang Xiang ( 185 - -269 ) , courtesy name Xiuzheng ( 休徵 ) , was a minister of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period .
Louise Gibson Annand - MacFarquhar MBE ( 27 May 1915 -- 6 January 2012 ) was a Scottish painter and film - maker .
Terry Hollindrake ( 21 December 1934 -- 29 January 2015 ) was an English professional rugby league footballer of the 1950s and 1960s , playing at representative level for Great Britain and Yorkshire , and at club level for Keighley , Hull and Bramley .
Princess Januária of Brazil ( Portuguese pronunciation : ( ʒɐnuˈaɾiɐ mɐˈɾiɐ ) ; Januária Maria Joana Carlota Leopoldina Cândida Francisca Xavier de Paula Micaela Gabriela Rafaela Gonzaga ; 11 March 1822 -- 13 March 1901 ) was a Brazilian princess and Portuguese infanta ( princess ) .
Henry Addington , 1st Viscount Sidmouth , PC ( 30 May 1757 -- 15 February 1844 ) was a British statesman who served as Prime Minister from 1801 to 1804 .
Susanne Lothar ( 15 November 1960 -- 21 July 2012 ) was a German film , television and stage actress .
Ana Rosa Tornero ( 1907 - -1984 ) was a Bolivian writer , journalist , teacher , social reformer and a feminist .
Jack Suchet ( 10 May 1908 -- 9 September 2001 ) was a South African - born English consultant obstetrician and gynaecologist , who carried out research on the use of penicillin in the treatment of venereal disease with Sir Alexander Fleming in London .
Mingyi Nyo died on 24 November 1530 , and was succeeded by his son Tabinshweti .
Charles Rich , 4th Earl of Warwick ( 28 June 1611 -- 29 May 1673 ) , styled The Honourable Charles Rich until 1658 , was an English peer and politician .
Valery Ustyuzhin ( Russian : Валерий Устюжин , 1945 -- 2 September 2010 ) was a Soviet heavyweight weightlifter .
Hillel Seidel ( Hebrew : הלל זיידל‎ , 9 October 1920 -- 14 February 1999 ) was an Israeli politician who served as a member of the Knesset for the Independent Liberals and Likud between 1974 and 1981 .
Muhammad Ibrahim Nugud ( 1930 -- 22 March 2012 ) was a Sudanese politician who was Secretary - General of the Sudanese Communist Party .
Sami al - Jundi ( 1921 - 1996 ) was a Syrian Ba'athist politician , and a follower of Michel Aflaq .
Cornelio Da Montalcino was a Franciscan friar who had embraced Judaism , and was burned alive on the Campo dei Fiori in Rome , Italy , in 1554 .
Hermann Georg of Limburg , count of Limburg and Bronckhorst ( 1540 -- 1574 ) , son of Georg of Limburg , count of Limburg and Bronckhorst .

Doreen Sloane ( 24 February 1934 in Birkenhead , the Wirral , Cheshire , England , UK -- 8 April 1990 in Liverpool , England , UK ) was an English actress best known for her roles in the soap operas Coronation Street , Emmerdale and Brookside .
Ignaz Kögler ( called Lai in Chinese ) ( 11 May 1680 -- 30 March 1746 ) was a German Jesuit missionary in Qing China .
Don Alfonso Fadrique ( English : Alfonso Frederick , Catalan : N'Anfós Frederic d'Aragó ) ( died 1338 ) was the eldest and illegitimate son of Frederick II of Sicily .
James Gibbon ( 1819 - -1888 ) was a land speculator and politician in Queensland , Australia .
William Howard Hay , MD ( 1866 -- 1940 ) was a New York doctor , author , lecturer , and founder of The East Aurora Sun and Diet Sanatorium .
Sir Frederick Richard Jordan KCMG ( 1881 - -1949 ) was an Australian barrister , the 9th Chief Justice of New South Wales and Lieutenant Governor of New South Wales .
André E. Lalonde ( 1955 - 2012 ) was a Canadian geologist and former dean of the Faculty of Science at the University of Ottawa .
Patti Laursen ( 1927 - -2013 ) was an internationally renowned classical music recording producer .
Lady Dorothea Du Bois ( 1728 - -1774 ) was an Irish writer .
Saint Cera of Ireland ( alternately Chera , Chier , Ciara , Cyra , Keira , Kiara , Cier , Ciar ) was an abbess in the 7th century who died in 679 .
George Arnold Wood ( 7 June 1865 -- 14 October 1928 ) was an English Australian historian notable for writing an early work on Australian history entitled The Discovery of Australia .
Máel Dúin mac Áedo ( died 786 ) was a possible King of Munster from the Eóganacht Locha Léin branch of the Eóganachta .
Elizabeth Percy , Countess of Northumberland ( née Wriothesley ; 1646 -- 19 September 1690 ) , was a British courtier .
John Bonett was the pen name of John Hubert Arthur Coulson ( 10 August 1906 -- 21 January 1989 ) , an English author , best known for numerous mystery and detective novels written in collaboration with his wife , Emery Bonett .
Philibert Jacques Melotte ( 29 January 1880 -- 30 March 1961 ) was a British astronomer whose parents immigrated from Belgium .
George Donne , ( 1605 - 1639 ) , a bit player in the establishment of Virginia , is described by historian Brent Tarter as , `` the less talented son of the clergyman and poet John Donne . ''
Cater Rand ( 9 December 1749 in Lewes , Sussex , England -- 21 December 1825 ) , his father , Charles Rand ? - 1763 had been born in Colchester , Essex , but relocated as a boy to Sussex in 1714 .
Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge ( Mary Adelaide Wilhelmina Elizabeth ; 27 November 1833 -- 27 October 1897 ) was a member of the British Royal Family , a granddaughter of George III and great - grandmother of Elizabeth II . She held the title of Duchess of Teck through marriage .
Family BASIC or Famicom BASIC is the consumer product for programming Nintendo 's Family Computer video game console of Japan .

PC Paintbrush is graphics editing software created by the ZSoft Corporation in 1985 for computers running the MS - DOS operating system .
Lords of the Realm is a turn - based strategy computer game published and developed by Impressions Games .
Space Combat is a game produced by Laminar Research to provide a simulation of space combat with accurate physics , unlike most other games of the same genre .
Bumpy Road is a platforming video game developed and published by Simogo for iOS and Mac . The game employs a unique control scheme : the player moves the road under a car instead of the car itself to achieve the objectives of the game .
ESPN International Winter Sports 2002 is a sports video game released in 2002 by Konami .
Arlington Horse Racing is a horse racing arcade game released by Strata / Incredible Technologies in 1990 , based on the Arlington Park race track .
Rick Dangerous is a series of two platform games released by Core Design ( who would later make Tomb Raider ) in the 1980s .
Screen Sharing is a VNC client by Apple Inc. included as part of Mac OS X v10.5 .
Mega Man X4 , originally released in Japan as Rockman X4 ( ロックマンX4 ) , is a video game developed by Capcom .
GT Cube is a racing video game release in 2003 by MTO for GameCube .

Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2 , stylized as Ninja Gaiden Σ2 , is an enhanced port of the 2008 Xbox 360 video game Ninja Gaiden II , and developed by Team Ninja exclusively for the PlayStation 3 .
Zero Gunner is a shoot 'em up developed by Psikyo and released in 1997 .
Dead or Alive 5 Plus ( stylized as Dead or Alive 5 + and abbreviated to DOA5 + ) is a fighting game in the Dead or Alive series , developed by Team Ninja in partnership with Sega AM2 and released by Tecmo Koei for the PlayStation Vita in March 2013 .

The Pajama Sam series is a collection of point and click children 's adventure and puzzle games originally created by Humongous Entertainment .

PGA Tour Golf Team Challenge is a trackball based golf arcade game series manufactured by Global VR of San Jose , California .

Disney Sports Soccer , known as Disney Sports Football in Europe , is a 2002 sports video game released by Konami .
Smashing Drive is a racing video game developed and published by Gaelco and distributed by Namco .
Subwar 2050 is a futuristic 3D submarine simulator computer game developed by Particle Systems Ltd. , Michael Powell acting as the lead designer , and published by MicroProse Software , Inc. The game was released in 1993 for DOS and 1994 for Amiga and Amiga CD32 .
LostWinds is a 2008 platform video game developed by Frontier Developments and published for the Wii as a launch title for WiiWare .
IBM SPSS Modeler 14.0 was the first release of Modeler by IBM IBM SPSS Modeler 15 , released in June 2012 , introduced significant new functionality for Social Network Analysis and Entity Analytics .

Guild Wars Nightfall is a fantasy Action RPG and the third stand - alone campaign in the Guild Wars computer game series developed by Seattle - based game developer studio ArenaNet , a subsidiary of NCSOFT corporation .
Grandmaster Chess is a 1993 video game to play chess for PC DOS platform develop by IntraCorp and its subsidiary Capstone that was focused on neural network technology and an artificial intelligence ( AI ) able to learn from mistakes .
Toontown Online was a massively multiplayer online role - playing game , developed by Disney Interactive and published by The Walt Disney Company .
Armor Battle is a multiplayer game released by Mattel for its Intellivision video game system in 1979 .

The product was originally developed in the early 1980s by Canadian company Quantum Software Systems , later renamed QNX Software Systems and ultimately acquired by BlackBerry in 2010 .

NHL Eastside Hockey Manager is an ice hockey management simulation game developed by Sports Interactive ( SI Games ) and published by Sega .

Cubixx HD is a puzzle game developed by UK - based studio Laughing Jackal released on the PlayStation Network in Europe on August 17 , 2011 and September 20 , 2011 in North America .
Blood Junkie ( originally filmed under the working title Rocky Trails ) is a 2010 American independent comedy horror movie that was written and directed by Drew Rosas .
Vikatakavi ( Malayalam : വികടകവി ) is a 1984 Malayalam film written and directed by Hariharan .
The Joy of Life ( 2005 ) is an experimental landscape documentary by filmmaker Jenni Olson about the history of suicide and the Golden Gate Bridge , and the adventures of a butch lesbian in San Francisco , California .

On January 6 , 2009 UST Inc. was purchased by Altria .

Xonox was one of many small video game companies to fold during the Video Game Crash of 1983 .
When Æthelflæd died in 918 , Ælfwynn , her daughter by Æthelred , succeeded as ' Second Lady of the Mercians ' , but within six months Edward had deprived her of all authority in Mercia and taken her into Wessex .
The League of Communists of Serbia ( Serbo - Croatian : Savez komunista Srbije , Савез комуниста Србије , SKS ) was the Serbian branch of the League of Communists of Yugoslavia , the sole legal party of Yugoslavia from 1945 to 1990 .

Alberto - Culver was purchased by the Anglo - Dutch consumer goods company Unilever on September 27 , 2010 for US$ 3.7 billion .
Eskilstunahus County , or Eskilstunahus län , was a county of the Swedish Empire from 1634 to 1683 , named after the county seat of Eskilstuna House .

The Dominican Party ( Spanish : Partido Dominicano , PD ) was the de facto only political party in the Dominican Republic during the dictatorship of Rafael Trujillo , who ruled the country from 1930 to 1961 .
Alpha Rho Upsilon ( ΑΡΥ ; usually pronounced ARU ) was a fraternity at Bowdoin College in Brunswick , Maine , from 1946 until it was disbanded in 1990 .

The Cheng Han ( simplified Chinese : 成汉 ; traditional Chinese : 成漢 ; pinyin : Chénghàn ; 303 or 304 - 347 ) was a state of the Sixteen Kingdoms during the Jin Dynasty ( 265 - 420 ) in China .
The Right Honourable Board of Commissioners for the Affairs of India ( commonly known as the India Board or the Board of Control ) was an arm of the Government of the United Kingdom responsible for managing the Government 's interest in British India and the East India Company between 1784 and 1858 .
The Bolognese Republic was proclaimed in 1796 in the Central Italian city of Bologna .
The Juzan was a French automobile manufactured only in 1897 ; it was a light motorised quadricycle along De Dion lines .

Established in 1672 for Bernhard , fourth son of Wilhelm , Duke of Saxe - Weimar , Saxe - Jena was reincorporated into Saxe - Weimar on the extinction of Bernhard 's line in 1690 .

The Khanate of Khiva ( Persian : خانات خیوه‎‎ , Uzbek : ' خیوه خانلیگی ' ) was a Central Asian state that existed in the historical region of Khwarezm from 1511 to 1920 , except for a period of Persian occupation by Nadir Shah between 1740 - -1746 .
In August 2002 , Presto Studios shut down new development after the release of an Xbox title Whacked!.
Rengsjöbilen ( the Rengsjö car ) , Jonsson or just `` Bilen '' ( the car ) was the names given to a series of ten cars made by sawmill owner Anders Jonsson in Rengsjö , Hälsingland between 1914 and 1916 .

The General Captaincy of Chile ( Capitanía General de Chile ) or Gobernación de Chile , was a colony of the Spanish Empire from 1541 to 1818 , the year in which it declared itself independent , becoming the Republic of Chile .
Drug Emporium is the name of a discount drug store corporation , founded in 1977 in Columbus , Ohio , that was sold to several different buyers during 2000 to 2001 .
Renaissance Broadcasting , founded in 1982 by Michael Finkelstien , was a company that owned several UHF television stations , it was sold to Tribune Broadcasting in 1997 .

Christopher Elton is a British pianist , former Head of the Keyboard department of the Royal Academy of Music in London and a professor emeritus of the University of London .
Melissa L. Tatum is the research professor of law and director of the Indigenous Peoples Law and Policy Program at the University of Arizona 's James E. Rogers College of Law .
Juan Ramón de la Fuente Ramírez ( born 5 September 1951 in Mexico City ) is a Mexican psychiatrist , academician and politician who served as Secretary of Health in the cabinet of President Ernesto Zedillo ( 1994 - -1999 ) and as rector of the National Autonomous University of Mexico ( UNAM ) from 1999 to 2007 .
Nurith Aviv is Professor at La Fémis ( Paris ) , and was , in 1975 , the first woman in France to be officially recognized as a Director of Photography by the CNC ( Centre National de la cinematographie ) .
Zidane Zeraoui El Awad is a Mexican professor and researcher of Algerian origin who specializes in international relations and the Middle East at the Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education .
Sander Griffioen ( born 31 May 1941 ) is a Dutch philosopher , and Emeritus Professor for intercultural philosophy at the Vrije Universiteit in Amsterdam .
Kristin Ross ( born 1953 ) is a professor of comparative literature at New York University .
Steven Johnston is the American , Neal A. Maxwell Chair in Political Theory , Public Policy , and Public Service in the Department of Political Science at the University of Utah .
Lieutenant general Carlos Alberto dos Santos Cruz is a Brazilian military officer who previously held the post of Force Commander of the United Nations ' peacekeeping force in the Democratic Republic of the Congo ( known by its acronym , MONUSCO ) .
Robert R. Shannon is Professor Emeritus of Optical Sciences at the University of Arizona College of Optical Sciences .
Daniel S. Rokhsar is a professor in the departments of Physics and of Molecular and Cell Biology at University of California , Berkeley and Head of the Plant Genomics Program at the Joint Genome Institute of the United States Department of Energy .
Emery Bopp ( May 13 , 1924 -- February 1 , 2007 ) was an artist and long - time chairman of the Division of Art , Bob Jones University .
Manfred Frank ( born March 22 , 1945 ) is a German philosopher , emeritus professor of philosophy at the University of Tübingen .
Alan Mackworth is a Professor of Computer Science and Canada Research Chair in Artificial Intelligence in the Department of Computer Science at the University of British Columbia .
Karen Brazell held a PhD from Columbia University , and was , until her death , Goldwin Smith Professor Emeritus of Japanese Literature and Theatre at Cornell University .
Daniel W. Drezner ( born August 28 , 1968 ) is an American professor of international politics at The Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University , an author of books and op - ed pieces , a blogger , and a commentator .
Joel E. Siegel ( 1940 -- 11 March 2004 ) was a professor of English and film studies at Georgetown University , a film and music critic , a music producer , and a lyricist .
Kathrin Bringmann ( born 8 May 1977 ) is a German number theorist in the University of Cologne , Germany , who has made fundamental contributions to the theory of mock theta functions .
Professor John Haffenden FBA FRSL is Emeritus Professor of English Literature at the University of Sheffield .
Lindsay Moran ( born 18 December 1969 ) is a former clandestine officer for the Central Intelligence Agency .
N'Gai Croal is a video game critic and consultant , previously employed by Newsweek , currently involved in his own consultancy company .
Cheick Sidi Diarra ( born 31 May 1957 , in Kayes ) previously served as United Nations Special Adviser on Africa and High Representative for the Least Developed Countries , Landlocked Developing Countries and Small Island Developing States ( OSAA / OHRLLS ) .
Hassan Hanafi ( حسن حنفی ) ( born 1935 in Cairo , Egypt ) is a professor and chairs the philosophy department at Cairo University .
Anjan Chakravartty is an analytic philosopher and a professor of philosophy at the University of Notre Dame .
T. S. Kalyanaraman ( born 1951 ) is an Indian businessman best known as the chairman and managing director of Kalyan Jewellers and Kalyan Developers .
Gwendoline Kirby was a nurse , and matron of Great Ormond Street Hospital .
Ragnar Knoph ( 24 October 1894 -- 25 December 1938 ) was a Norwegian jurist and professor of jurisprudence at the University of Oslo .
Martin Hume Johnson ( born 1944 ) FRS FMedSci FSB FRCOG is Emeritus Professor of Reproductive Sciences in the Department of Physiology , Development and Neuroscience ( PDN ) at the University of Cambridge .
Murray Barnson Emeneau ( February 28 , 1904 -- August 29 , 2005 ) was an emeritus professor and founder of the Department of Linguistics at the University of California , Berkeley .
Susan Schulten is an American historian , and professor at the University of Denver .
Jeffrey A. Harvey ( born February 15 , 1955 in San Antonio , Texas ) is a Professor of Physics and string theorist at University of Chicago .
George Auckland is a UK television and digital media executive , now retired after a long career at the BBC .

In 1799 Esaias Tegnér , hitherto educated in the country , entered Lund University , where he graduated in philosophy in 1802 , and continued as tutor until 1810 , when he was elected Greek lecturer .

The Flaid was a Belgian automobile manufactured from 1920 until 1921 in Liège .
The Trussell Trust is a NGO and charity , based in Salisbury , UK , that co - ordinates the only nationwide network of food banks in the country .

Rural King Supply is a farm supply store based in Mattoon , Illinois , United States .

Boticca is a London - based retail website for jewelry and fashion accessories , that features a selection emerging fashion designers .

Total Wine & More has about 5,000 employees , including 500 employees at their corporate headquarters in Potomac , Maryland and 800 wine specialists who must demonstrate wine knowledge before they are invited to join the company .

Jean Jacques Émile Cheysson ( 18 May 1836 -- 7 February 1910 ) was a French ingenieur .
Pudukkottai Ulaganathan Pillai Chinnappa ( 5 May 1916 -- 23 September 1951 ) , also popularly known as P. U. Chinnappa , was a popular singer and Tamil movie actor during the 1930s and from Pudukottai , Tamil Nadu , India .
Antonio Visentini ( 21 November 1688 -- 26 June 1782 ) was an Italian architectural designer , painter and engraver , known for his architectural fantasies and capricci , the author of treatises on perspective and a professor at the Venetian Academy .

Juan Eduardo Cirlot Laporta ( April 9 , 1916 -- May 11 , 1973 ) was a Spanish poet , art critic , hermeneutist , mythologist , and musician .
Vlad Georgescu ( 1937 - -1988 ) , Romanian historian , was the director of the Romanian - language department of Radio Free Europe between 1983 and 1988 .
Bernardo Bertolucci ( Italian : ( berˈnardo bertoˈluttʃi ) ; born 16 March 1941 ) is an Italian film director and screenwriter , whose films include The Conformist , Last Tango in Paris , 1900 , The Last Emperor , The Sheltering Sky and The Dreamers .

Francis Pasche ( French : ( paʃ ) ; 7 May 1910 -- 12 September 1996 ) was a French psychoanalyst .
Isaac ibn Sid was a Spanish - Jewish astronomer ; he flourished at the Toledo School of Translators in the second half of the thirteenth century .
Alexander Görlach ( born December 28 , 1976 ) is a German author and syndicated columnist .
André Weil ( /veɪ/ ; French : ( ɑ̃dʁe vɛj ) ; 6 May 1906 -- 6 August 1998 ) was an influential French mathematician of the 20th century , known for his foundational work in number theory and algebraic geometry .
Johann Albrecht Adelgrief ( died 11 October 1636 ) was an alleged German prophet , born in the environs of Elbląg ( Elbing ) , Poland .

Vincenzo Gemito ( July 16 , 1852 - March 1 , 1929 ) was an Italian sculptor and artist .

Fermín Solís Campos ( born May 16 , 1972 ) is a Spanish cartoonist , animator , and illustrator .

Attilio Piccioni ( 14 July 1892 -- 10 March 1976 ) was an Italian politician , born in Poggio Bustone .
Yi Kwang - su ( Hangul : 이광수 ; 1892 , Chongju -- 1950 ) was a Korean writer and independence activist .
Jacques Boyceau , sieur de la Barauderie ( ca . 1560 -- 1633 ) was a French garden designer , the superintendent of royal gardens under Louis XIII , whose posthumously produced Traité du iardinage selon les raisons de la nature et de l'art .

Michelangelo Pistoletto ( born 25 June 1933 ) is an Italian painter , action and object artist , and art theorist .
Paul Auguste Hariot ( 1854 - 5 July 1917 ) , the son of Louis Hariot ( also a pharmacist ) , was a French pharmacist and noted phycologist , best known for his 1900 publication Atlas Colorié des Plantes Médicinales Indigènes .

Jean - Henri Claude Mangin was a French magistrate ( 7 March 1786 Metz- 1835 ) .

Houshang Golshiri ( Persian : هوشنگ گلشیری‎‎ ; 1937 -- June 6 , 2000 ) was an Iranian fiction writer , critic and editor .
Adolphus William Young ( 1814 -- 4 November 1885 ) was an English solicitor who spent some years in New South Wales and became a member of the New South Wales Legislative Council .
Wolfram Adalbert Scheffler ( born 1956 in Karl - Marx - Stadt ) is a German painter and artist .

Mihkel Mutt ( born February 18 , 1953 , in Tartu ) is an Estonian writer , essayist , columnist and editor .
Sylvie Guillaume ( born 11 June 1962 in Antony , Hauts - de - Seine ) is a French politician and Member of the European Parliament for the South - East France constituency .

Michael Scammell ( born 1935 ) is an English author , biographer and translator of Slavic literature .

Otakar Ševčík ( 22 March 1852 -- 18 January 1934 ) was a Czech violinist and influential teacher .

Matteo Maria Boiardo ( Italian pronunciation : ( matˈtɛːo maˈriːa boˈjardo ) ; 1434 - 41 -- 19/20 December 1494 ) was an Italian Renaissance poet .

Marco Follini ( born on 26 September 1954 ) is an Italian centre - wing politician .
Pierre - Augustin Hulin ( September 6 , 1758 -- January 9 , 1841 ) was a French general under Napoleon Bonaparte who took part in the storming of the Bastille , the trial of the Duke d'Enghien , and the foiling of the Malet coup .
Nicky Harman is a UK - based prize - winning literary translator , working from Chinese to English .
Jean Bernard Bossu ( 1720 - -1792 ) was a captain in the French navy , adventurer and explorer .

William Abbot ( 12 June 1790 -- 1 June 1843 ) , was an English actor .
John Venn , FRS , FSA , ( 4 August 1834 -- 4 April 1923 ) was an English logician and philosopher noted for introducing the Venn diagram , used in the fields of set theory , probability , logic , statistics , and computer science .
Anders Abraham Grafström ( 10 January 1790 -- 24 July 1870 ) was a Swedish historian , priest and poet .
Rodrigo Sánchez de Arévalo ( Latin : Rodericus Zamorensis ; Santa María la Real de Nieva , diocese of Segovia , 1404 -- 4 October 1470 ) was a Spanish churchman , historian and political theorist .
David Gilly ( 7 January 1748 -- 5 May 1808 ) was a German architect and architecture - tutor in Prussia , known as the father of the architect Friedrich Gilly .
Ludwik Fleck ( 11 July 1896 -- 5 June 1961 ) was a Polish and Israeli physician and biologist who did important work in epidemic typhus in Lwów , Poland , with Rudolf Weigl and in the 1930s developed the concept of the `` Denkkollektiv '' ( `` thought collective '' ) .
Louis Renou ( French : ( ʁənu ) ; 26 October 1896 -- 18 August 1966 ) was the pre - eminent French Indologist of the twentieth century .

Pandit Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande ( August 10 , 1860 -- September 19 , 1936 ) was an Indian musicologist who wrote the first modern treatise on Hindustani Classical Music ( The north Indian variety of Indian classical music ) , an art which had been propagated earlier for a few centuries mostly through oral traditions .

Giovanni Galbaio was the eighth Doge of Venice ( 787 - -804 ) according to tradition , but only the sixth historically verifiable one .

Semicassis granulata undulata is a Mediterranean subspecies of Semicassis granulata , the Scotch bonnet , a medium - sized sea snail , a marine gastropod mollusc in the subfamily Cassinae , the helmet snails and bonnet snails .
Widdringtonia whytei , the Mulanje cypress , is a species of Widdringtonia native to Malawi , where it is endemic to the Mulanje Massif at altitudes of 1,830 - 2,550 m. It has become endangered as a result of over - harvesting for its wood , and an increase in the frequency of wildfires due to human activity .
Madascincus arenicola is an extant species of skink described in 2011 , and endemic to the Ampombofofo and Forêt d'Orangea regions of Antsiranana Province , in northern Madagascar .
Distorsio anus , common name the common distorsio , is a species of medium - sized sea snail , a marine gastropod mollusk in the family Personidae , the Distortio snails .
Leymus multicaulis , also known as manystem wild rye or manystem lyme grass , is a species of the Leymus genus .
Kurt Equiluz ( born 13 June 1929 in Vienna ) is an Austrian classical tenor in opera and concert , known for recording works of Johann Sebastian Bach with Nikolaus Harnoncourt and Helmuth Rilling , a member of the Vienna State Opera as a tenor buffo from 1957 until 1983 .
Miriam Gauci ( born April 3 , 1957 ) is a Maltese operatic soprano , particularly associated with lyric Italian roles .
Anne Sharp ( 24 October 1916 -- 25 August 2011 ) was a Scottish coloratura soprano particularly associated with the operas of Benjamin Britten .
Stephen Mark Brown is an internationally known opera tenor .
Edna Garabedian is an American operatic mezzo - soprano , voice teacher , and opera director .
